reviews.text:
Not bad but not cheap as well.
$9 set gets u a small bowl n otah.
Will be hungry fast.

Taste wise not so bad.
It's like thick vermicelli in super rich curry broth with coconut milk aroma, unlike the usual Laksa in Malaysia using thin vermicelli. A nice flavour. Otak-otak Is good too.

Visited around 6 PM and ordered two sets of laksa‚Äîone with otah and the other with muah chee. The laksa tasted pretty average, nothing particularly special about it. The unique aspect was that they don‚Äôt provide chopsticks.

The otah was just your standard fare, while the muah chee was overly sweet with an excessive amount of sugar mixed with the peanut.
Best laksa I ever had.  Thick coconut milk gravy and it is gluten free. No wheat flour or soya sauce. Ask for no fishcake (no gluten-free) Contain dried shrimp and fresh prawn and clam

Brought my stainless steel food container to buy 2 portions of laksa. Was told that they will charge $0.50 per portion even we use our own container. Reason is that they will give more gravy. When I tell them I don‚Äôt need more gravy, the counter staff said the 50 cents still apply. In the end paid extra $1.00. Those need to ta pau no need to bring own container as they will charge u $0.50 whatever the case. Just left the shop.üòû
